        <iri>
          <value>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#Vehicle</value>
          <annotations>
            <annotation>
              <subject>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#Vehicle</subject>
              <property>http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment</property>
              <object>
                <lexicalForm>Common definition in Directives 2016/797, 2016/798:
 a railway vehicle suitable for circulation on wheels on railway lines, with or without traction; a vehicle is composed of one or more structural and functional subsystems

ERA vocabulary 3.0.0: A specific vehicle or wagon able to operate over railway lines.</lexicalForm>
                <datatype/>
                <language>en</language>
              </object>
            </annotation>
            <annotation>
              <subject>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#Vehicle</subject>
              <property>http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label</property>
              <object>
                <lexicalForm>Vehicle</lexicalForm>
                <datatype/>
                <language>en</language>
              </object>
            </annotation>
            <annotation>
              <subject>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#Vehicle</subject>
              <property>http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment</property>
              <object>
                <lexicalForm>Considered to be the atomic part of a piece of rolling stock, although disassembly may be carried out in special circumstances. Example: a TALGO or TGV trailer does not rest on two axles resp. bogies, but has a distinct carbody and it considered a vehicle (called "trailer").  Further example: an articulated wagon (3-axle, e.g. carrying cars) is generally considered a single vehicle although it has two distinct chassis. So the distinction vehicle / formation is conventional; being "atomic" in operations is a necessary condition, but not a sufficient one to be called vehicle.</lexicalForm>
                <datatype/>
                <language>en</language>
              </object>
            </annotation>
          </annotations>
        </iri>
        <iri>
          <value>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#coupledTo</value>
          <functional/>
          <inverseFunctional/>
          <symmetric/>
          <irreflexive/>
          <annotations>
            <annotation>
              <subject>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#coupledTo</subject>
              <property>http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label</property>
              <object>
                <lexicalForm>coupled to</lexicalForm>
                <datatype>http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#PlainLiteral</datatype>
                <language/>
              </object>
            </annotation>
            <annotation>
              <subject>https://cdm.ovh/rst/cons/cons#coupledTo</subject>
              <property>http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment</property>
              <object>
                <lexicalForm>Symmetric property "coupled to" relates two extremities of two distinct Rolling stock items (hence the "to" in the label). The property is expressed irrespectively of the type of coupling (mechanical, virtual) or coupler (UIC, Scharfenberg...).</lexicalForm>
                <datatype/>
                <language>en</language>
              </object>
            </annotation>
          </annotations>
        </iri>
